<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="58" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1493,2025]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1493,1519]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Cerci usually reaching beyond lower margin of epandrium in lateral view; surstylus much longer than distiphallus (
<figureCitation box="[361,449,1532,1558]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1208,1232]" captionTargetBox="[186,1404,454,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,395,1184]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 27. Species of Sepedon spinipes group, male terminalia. 20 – 23. S. americana. 24 – 27. S. spinipes. 20, 24. Lateral view. 21, 25. Hypandrium in lateral view. 22, 26. Aedeagus in lateral view. 23, 27. Epiphallus in caudal view. Scales: 0.5 mm (Figs 20, 24), 0.3 mm (Figs 21 – 23, 24 – 27)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191321/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[416,449,1532,1558]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
); emargination of basal part of hypandrium conspicuous (
<figureCitation box="[1130,1219,1532,1558]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1208,1232]" captionTargetBox="[186,1404,454,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,395,1184]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 27. Species of Sepedon spinipes group, male terminalia. 20 – 23. S. americana. 24 – 27. S. spinipes. 20, 24. Lateral view. 21, 25. Hypandrium in lateral view. 22, 26. Aedeagus in lateral view. 23, 27. Epiphallus in caudal view. Scales: 0.5 mm (Figs 20, 24), 0.3 mm (Figs 21 – 23, 24 – 27)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191321/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[1186,1219,1532,1558]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="25.0">25</number>
</figureCitation>
); distiphallus only short, barely longer than epiphallus and not dilated apically (
<figureCitation box="[862,950,1571,1597]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 27" captionStartId="7.[151,269,1208,1232]" captionTargetBox="[186,1404,454,1147]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,395,1184]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 27. Species of Sepedon spinipes group, male terminalia. 20 – 23. S. americana. 24 – 27. S. spinipes. 20, 24. Lateral view. 21, 25. Hypandrium in lateral view. 22, 26. Aedeagus in lateral view. 23, 27. Epiphallus in caudal view. Scales: 0.5 mm (Figs 20, 24), 0.3 mm (Figs 21 – 23, 24 – 27)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191321/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[917,950,1571,1597]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1493,2025]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
At first glance, 
<taxonomicName box="[386,515,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis box="[386,401,1610,1635]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[417,515,1610,1635]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
might be mistaken for the new Palaearctic species, 
<taxonomicName box="[1143,1331,1610,1635]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hecate" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1143,1331,1610,1635]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Sepedon hecate</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1340,1436,1609,1635]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1340,1436,1609,1635]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
However, detailed comparison of both species shows reliable differences. 
<taxonomicName box="[1022,1148,1648,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis box="[1022,1037,1649,1674]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1052,1148,1649,1674]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is generally smaller and paler, the black orbital spot is of a different shape, the pedicel is stouter, the dark longitudinal stripe above the postpronotal callus and notopleuron is almost indistinct, the katatergite is setulose in the posterior part, cell r 
<number box="[1411,1420,1741,1755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[1429,1437,1741,1755]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="5.0">5</number>
is parallel-sided, and the posterior crossvein is much more bowed than sinuate (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1183,1767,1793]" captionStart="FIGURES 28 – 29" captionStartId="8.[151,269,686,710]" captionTargetBox="[432,1143,514,655]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[430,1146,514,658]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 28 – 29. Wings of Sepedon species. 28. S. hecate sp. nov. 29. S. spinipes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/191322/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[1150,1183,1767,1793]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="28.0">28</number>
</figureCitation>
). Distinct differences were also found in the shape of the male terminalia, as noted above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="59" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1493,2025]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,152,448]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="59" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,1844,1870]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Distribution.</emphasis>
Details of the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[764,894,1844,1870]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis box="[764,779,1845,1870]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[798,894,1845,1870]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were recently re-examined in representative material from widespread parts of the distribution area and also compared with earlier published data from the Palaearctic, if they were accompanied by sufficiently detailed figures of the male terminalia. It is thus confirmed that 
<taxonomicName box="[334,463,1961,1987]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Sepedon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis box="[334,349,1961,1986]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[365,463,1961,1986]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs over the large territory from 
<collectingCountry box="[903,991,1961,1987]" name="Ireland" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Ireland</collectingCountry>
, the British Isles, and Scandinavia to North Africa (
<collectingCountry box="[320,431,1999,2025]" name="Morocco" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Morocco</collectingCountry>
) and from 
<collectingCountry box="[563,664,1999,2025]" name="Portugal" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Portugal</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[703,818,1999,2025]" name="Mongolia" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
and the Russian Far East. However, it has not been found in 
<collectingCountry box="[257,324,152,178]" name="Japan" pageId="8" pageNumber="59">Japan</collectingCountry>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Sueyoshi" box="[378,555,152,178]" pageId="8" pageNumber="60" refString="Sueyoshi, M. (2001) A revision of Japanese Sciomyzidae (Diptera) with descriptions of three new species. Entomological Science 4, 485 - 506." type="journal article" year="2001">
Sueyoshi 
<number box="[492,555,152,178]" pageId="8" pageNumber="59" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
